===Slavic languages===

====Czech====
There are three diphthongs in [[Czech phonology|Czech]]:

*{{IPA|/aʊ̯/}} as in ''auto'' (almost exclusively in words of foreign origin)
*{{IPA|/eʊ̯/}} as in ''euro'' (in words of foreign origin only)
*{{IPA|/oʊ̯/}} as in ''koule''

The vowel groups ''ia, ie, ii, io'', and  ''iu'' in foreign words are not regarded as diphthongs, they are pronounced with {{IPA|/j/}} between the vowels {{IPA|[ɪja, ɪjɛ, ɪjɪ, ɪjo, ɪju]}}.

====Serbo-Croatian====
*{{lang|sh|italic=no|i(j)e}}, as in {{lang|sh|mlijeko}}&lt;ref&gt;{{in lang|hr}} [http://www.vjesnik.hr/html/1999/05/11/nunu.htm Vjesnik] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20001121044500/http://www.vjesnik.hr/html/1999/05/11/nunu.htm |date=21 November 2000 }} Babić ne zagovara korijenski pravopis, nego traži da Hrvati ne piju mlijeko nego – mlieko&lt;/ref&gt;
is conventionally considered a diphthong. However, it is actually {{IPA|[ie]}} in hiatus or separated by a semivowel, {{IPA|[ije]}}.

Some [[Serbo-Croatian phonology|Serbo-Croatian]] dialects also have ''uo'', as in {{lang|sh|kuonj, ruod, uon}}&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |language=Croatian |url=http://www.matica.hr/Kolo/kolo0302.nsf/AllWebDocs/lisac1 |journal=[[Kolo (magazine)|Kolo]] |author=Josip Lisac |title=Štokavsko narječje: prostiranje i osnovne značajke |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217013643/http://www.matica.hr/Kolo/kolo0302.nsf/AllWebDocs/lisac1 |archivedate=17 February 2008 |df=dmy }}&lt;/ref&gt; whereas, in Standard Croatian and Serbian, these words are konj, rod, on.

===Finno-Ugric languages===

====Estonian====
{{Main|Estonian phonology}}

All nine vowels can appear as the first component of an Estonian diphthong, but only {{IPA|[ɑ e i o u]}} occur as the second component.

